1 rentals;
2 3. Intentionally refuses to pay or absconds without payment;
3 4. Fails to respond within five (5) days after receiving notice by certified
4 mail demanding return; and
5 5. Refuses to make an agreeable payment to a rental agency within thirty
6 (30) days of receipt of a late notice to a person sent by certified mail,
7 return receipt requested.
8 (2) Where compensation for services is ordinarily paid immediately upon the rendering
9 of the services, as in the case of hotels and restaurants, refusal to pay or absconding
10 without payment or offer to pay shall be prima facie evidence that the services were
11 obtained by deception as to intention to pay.
12 (3) In any prosecution for theft of gas, water, electricity, or other public service, where
13 the utility supplying the service had installed a meter or other device to record the
14 amount of service supplied, proof that:
15 (a) The meter or other device has been altered, tampered with, or bypassed in a
16 manner so as to prevent or reduce the recording thereof; or
17 (b) Service has been, after having been disconnected by the utility supplying
18 service, reconnected without authorization of the utility
19 shall be prima facie evidence of the intent to commit theft of service by the person
20 or persons obligated to pay for service supplied through the meter or other device.
21 (4) Theft of services is a Class B misdemeanor unless:
22 (a) The value of the service is five hundred dollars ($500) or more but less than
23 one thousand dollars ($1,000), in which case it is a Class A misdemeanor;
24 (b) The value of the service is one thousand dollars ($1,000) or more but less than
25 ten thousand dollars ($10,000), in which case it is a Class D felony;
26 (c) A person has three (3) or more convictions under paragraph (a) of this
27 subsection within the last five (5) years, in which case it is a Class D felony.
